st day on which Navy Days can fall, celebrated First Saturday and Sunday. (Netherlands)\nBULLET::::- Earliest day on which Youth Day can fall, while July 7 is the latest; celebrated on the first Sunday in July. (Singapore)\nBULLET::::- Armed Forces Day (Singapore)\nBULLET::::- Canada Day, formerly Dominion Day (Canada)\nBULLET::::- Children's Day (Pakistan)\nBULLET::::- Communist Party of China Founding Day (China)\nBULLET::::- Day of Officials and Civil Servants (Hungary)\nBULLET::::- Doctors' Day (India)\nBULLET::::- Emancipation Day (Netherlands Antilles)\nBULLET::::- Engineer's Day (Bahrain, Mexico)\nBULLET::::- Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Establishment Day (Hong Kong, China)\nBULLET::::- Independence Day (Burundi), celebrates the independence of Burundi from Belgium in 1962.\nBULLET::::- Independence Day (Rwanda)\nBULLET::::- Independence Day (Somalia)\nBULLET::::- International Tartan Day\nBULLET::::- July Morning (Bulgaria)\nBULLET::::- Keti Koti (Emancipation Day) (Suriname)\nBULLET::::- Madeira Day (Madeira, Portugal)\nBULLET::::- Moving Day (Quebec) (Canada)\nBULLET::::- Newfoundland and Labrador Memorial Day\nBULLET::::- Republic Day (Ghana)\nBULLET::::- Sir Seretse Khama Day (Botswana)\nBULLET::::- Territory Day (British Virgin Islands)\nBULLET::::- The first day of Van Mahotsav, celebrated until July 7. (India)\n\nBULLET::::- BBC: On This Day\nBULLET::::- On This Day in Canada\n"}
{"id": "15845", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15845", "title": "January 25", "text": "January 25\n\nBULLET::::- AD 41 – After a night of negotiation, Claudius is accepted as Roman Emperor by the Senate.\nBULLET::::- 750 – In the Battle of the Zab, the Abbasid rebels defeat the Umayyad Caliphate, leading to overthrow of the dynasty.\nBULLET::::- 1348 – A strong earthquake strikes the South Alpine region of Friuli in modern Italy, causing considerable damage to buildings as far away as Rome.\nBULLET::::- 1494 – Alfonso II becomes King of Naples.\nBULLET::::- 1515 – Coronation of Francis I of France takes place at Reims Cathedral, where the new monarch is anointed with the oil of Clovis and girt with the sword of Charlemagne.\nBULLET::::- 1533 – Henry VIII of England secretly marries his second wife Anne Boleyn.\nBULLET::::- 1554 – São Paulo, Brazil, is founded by Jesuit priests.\nBULLET::::- 1573 – Battle of Mikatagahara: In Japan, Takeda Shingen defeats Tokugawa Ieyasu.\nBULLET::::- 1575 – Luanda, the capital of Angola, is founded by the Portuguese navigator Paulo Dias de Novais.\nBULLET::::- 1704 – The Battle of Ayubale results in the destruction of most of the Spanish missions in Florida.\nBULLET::::- 1755 – Moscow University is established on Tatiana Day.\nBULLET::::- 1765 – Port Egmont, the first British settlement in the Falkland Islands near the southern tip of South America, is founded.\nBULLET::::- 1787 – Shays's Rebellion: The rebellion's largest confrontation, outside the Springfield Armory, results in the killing of four rebels and the wounding of twenty.\nBULLET::::- 1791 – The British Parliament passes the Constitutional Act of 1791 and splits the old Province of Quebec into Upper Canada and Lower Canada.\nBULLET::::- 1792 – The London Corresponding Society is founded.\nBULLET::::- 1858 – The \"Wedding March\" by Felix Mendelssohn is played at the marriage of Queen Victoria's daughter, Victoria, and Friedrich of Prussia, and becomes a popular wedding processional.\nBULLET::::- 1879 – The Bulgarian National Bank is founded.\nBULLET::::- 1881 – Thomas Edison and Alexander Graham Bell form the Oriental Telephone Company.\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Nellie Bly completes her round-the-world journey in 72 days.\nBULLET::::- 1909 – Richard Strauss's opera \"Elektra\" receives its debut performance at the Dresden State Opera.\nBULLET::::- 1915 – Alexander Graham Bell inaugurates U.S. transcontinental telephone service, speaking from New York to Thomas Watson in San Francisco.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – The Ukrainian People's Republic declares independence from Soviet Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1924 – The 1924 Winter Olympics opens in Chamonix, in the French Alps, inaugurating the Winter Olympic Games.\nBULLET::::- 1932 – Second Sino-Japanese War: The Chinese National Revolutionary Army begins the defense of Harbin.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – \"The Guiding Light\" debuts on NBC radio from Chicago. In 1952 it moves to CBS television, where it remains until September 18, 2009.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – Pope Pius XII elevates the Apostolic Vicariate of the Hawaiian Islands to the dignity of a diocese. It becomes the Roman Catholic Diocese of Honolulu.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: Thailand declares war on the United States and United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The Battle of the Bulge ends.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – The United Mine Workers rejoins the American Federation of Labor.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – United Nations Security Council Resolution 1 relating to Military Staff Committee is adopted.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Thomas Goldsmith Jr. files a patent for a \"Cathode Ray Tube Amusement Device\", the first ever electronic game.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – The first Emmy Awards are presented; the venue is the Hollywood Athletic Club.\nBULLET::::- 1960 – The National Association of Broadcasters reacts to the \"payola\" scandal by threatening fines for any disc jockeys who accept money for playing particular records.\nBULLET::::- 1961 – In Washington, D.C., President John F. Kennedy delivers the first live presidential television news conference.\nBULLET::::- 1961 – \"101 Dalmatians\" premiered from Walt Disney Productions.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Blue Ribbon Sports, which would later become Nike, is founded by University of Oregon track and field athletes.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – Brazilian Army captain Carlos Lamarca deserts in order to fight against the military dictatorship, taking with him ten machine guns and 63 rifles.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Charles Manson and three female \"Family\" members are found guilty of the 1969 Tate–LaBianca murders.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Idi Amin leads a coup deposing Milton Obote and becomes Uganda's president.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – Pope John Paul II starts his first official papal visits outside Italy to The Bahamas, Dominican Republic, and Mexico.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – Mother Teresa is honored with India's highest civilian award, the Bharat Ratna.\nBULLET::::- 1986 – The National Resistance Movement topples the government of Tito Okello in Uganda.\nBULLET::::- 1993 – Five people are shot outside the CIA Headquarters in Langley, Virginia. Two are killed and three wounded.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – The spacecraft \"Clementine\" by BMDO and NASA is launched.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – The Norwegian rocket incident: Russia almost launches a nuclear attack after it mistakes Black Brant XII, a Norwegian research rocket, for a US Trident missile.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – Billy Bailey becomes the last person to be hanged in the U.S.A.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – During a historic visit to Cuba, Pope John Paul II demands political reforms and the release of political prisoners while condemning US attempts to isolate the country.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – A suicide attack by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam on Sri Lanka's Temple of the Tooth kills eight and injures 25 others.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – A 6.0 Richter scale earthquake hits western Colombia killing at least 1,000.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – Invasion of Iraq: A group of people leave London, England, for Baghdad, Iraq, to serve as human shields, intending to prevent the U.S.-led coalition troops from bombing certain locations.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – A stampede at the Mandhradevi temple in Maharashtra, India kills at least 258.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – Mexican professional wrestler Juana Barraza is arrested in connection with the serial killing of at least ten elderly women.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – The first wave of the Egyptian revolution begins throughout the country, marked by street demonstrations, rallies, acts of civil disobedience, riots, labour strikes, and violent clashes.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – At least 50 people are killed and 120 people are injured in a prison riot in Barquisimeto, Venezuela.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – A clash in Mamasapano, Maguindanao in the Philippines killing 44 members of Special Action Force (SAF), at least 18 from the Moro Islamic Liberation Front and five from the Bangsamoro Islamic Freedom Fighters.\nBULLET::::- 2019 – A mining company's dam collapses in Brumadinho, Brazil, a south-eastern city, killing at least 7 people and leaving 200 missing.\n\nBULLET::::- 750 – Leo IV the Khazar, Byzantine emperor (d. 780)\nBULLET::::- 1408 – Katharina of Hanau, German countess regent (d. 1460)\nBULLET::::- 1459 – Paul Hofhaimer, Austrian organist and composer (d. 1537)\nBULLET::::- 1477 – Anne of Brittany (probable; d. 1514)\nBULLET::::- 1509 – Giovanni Morone, Italian cardinal (d. 1580)\nBULLET::::- 1526 – Adolf, Duke of Holstein-Gottorp (d. 1586)\nBULLET::::- 1615 – Govert Flinck, Dutch painter (d. 1660)\nBULLET::::- 1618 – Nicolaes Visscher I, Dutch engraver and cartographer (d. 1679)\nBULLET::::- 1627 – Robert Boyle, Irish-English chemist and physicist (d. 1691)\nBULLET::::- 1634 – Gaspar Fagel, Dutch politician and diplomat (d. 1688)\nBULLET::::- 1635 – Daniel Casper von Lohenstein, German writer, diplomat and lawyer (d. 1683)\nBULLET::::- 1640 – William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Devonshire, English soldier and politician, Lord Steward