{"id": "15847", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15847", "title": "January 11", "text": "January 11\n\nBULLET::::- 532 – Nika riots in Constantinople: A quarrel between supporters of different chariot teams—the Blues and the Greens—in the Hippodrome escalates into violence.\nBULLET::::- 630 – Conquest of Mecca: The prophet Muhammad and his followers conquer the city, Quraysh surrender.\nBULLET::::- 947 – Emperor Tai Zong of the Khitan-led Liao Dynasty invades the Later Jin, resulting in the destruction of the Later Jin.\nBULLET::::- 1055 – Theodora is crowned empress of the Byzantine Empire.\nBULLET::::- 1158 – Vladislaus II, Duke of Bohemia becomes King of Bohemia.\nBULLET::::- 1569 – First recorded lottery in England.\nBULLET::::- 1571 – Austrian nobility is granted freedom of religion.\nBULLET::::- 1654 – Arauco War: A Spanish army is defeated by local Mapuche-Huilliches as it tries to cross Bueno River in Southern Chile.\nBULLET::::- 1693 – A powerful earthquake destroys parts of Sicily and Malta.\nBULLET::::- 1759 – In Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, the first American life insurance company is incorporated.\nBULLET::::- 1779 – Ching-Thang Khomba is crowned King of Manipur.\nBULLET::::- 1787 – William Herschel discovers Titania and Oberon, two moons of Uranus.\nBULLET::::- 1805 – The Michigan Territory is created.\nBULLET::::- 1861 – American Civil War: Alabama secedes from the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: Battle of Arkansas Post: General John McClernand and Admiral David Dixon Porter capture the Arkansas River for the Union.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: encounters and sinks the off Galveston Lighthouse in Texas.\nBULLET::::- 1879 – The Anglo-Zulu War begins.\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Grand Canyon National Monument is created.\nBULLET::::- 1912 – Immigrant textile workers in Lawrence, Massachusetts, go on strike when wages are reduced in response to a mandated shortening of the work week.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – The Kingsland munitions factory explosion occurs as a result of sabotage.\nBULLET::::- 1922 – First use of insulin to treat diabetes in a human patient.\nBULLET::::- 1923 – Occupation of the Ruhr: Troops from France and Belgium occupy the Ruhr area to force Germany to make its World War I reparation payments.\nBULLET::::- 1927 – Louis B. Mayer, head of film studio Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (MGM), announces the creation of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, at a banquet in Los Angeles, California.\nBULLET::::- 1935 – Amelia Earhart becomes the first person to fly solo from Hawaii to California.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: Japanese forces capture Kuala Lumpur, the capital of the Federated Malay States.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: Japanese forces attack Tarakan in Borneo, Netherlands Indies (Battle of Tarakan)\nBULLET::::- 1943 – The Republic of China agrees to the Sino-British New Equal Treaty and the Sino-American New Equal Treaty.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – Italian-American anarchist Carlo Tresca is assassinated in New York City.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – Enver Hoxha, Secretary General of the Communist Party of Albania, declares the People's Republic of Albania with himself as head of state.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – The first \"networked\" television broadcasts took place as KDKA-TV in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania goes on the air connecting the east coast and mid-west programming.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – The African Convention is founded in Dakar, Senegal.\nBULLET::::- 1961 – Throgs Neck Bridge over the East River, linking New York City's boroughs of The Bronx and Queens, opens to road traffic.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – Cold War: While tied to its pier in Polyarny, the Soviet submarine B-37 is destroyed when fire breaks out in its torpedo compartment.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – An avalanche on Huascarán in Peru causes around 4,000 deaths.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Surgeon General of the United States Dr. Luther Terry, M.D., publishes the landmark report \"\" saying that smoking may be hazardous to health, sparking national and worldwide anti-smoking efforts.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – East Pakistan renames itself Bangladesh.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – Major League Baseball owners vote in approval of the American League adopting the designated hitter position.\nBULLET::::- 1986 – The Gateway Bridge, Brisbane, Queensland, Australia is officially opened.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – The Irish Government announces the end of a 15-year broadcasting ban on the IRA and its political arm Sinn Féin.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – Space Shuttle program: STS-72 launches from the Kennedy Space Center marking the start of the 74th Space Shuttle mission and the 10th flight of \"Endeavour\".\nBULLET::::- 1996 - Ryutaro Hashimoto, leader of the Liberal Democratic Party, becomes Prime Minister of Japan.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – Over 100 people are killed in the Sidi-Hamed massacre in Algeria.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – Illinois Governor George Ryan commutes the death sentences of 167 prisoners on Illinois's death row based on the Jon Burge scandal.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – One French soldier and 17 militants are killed in a failed attempt to free a French hostage in Bulo Marer, Somalia.\n\nBULLET::::- 347 – Theodosius I, Roman emperor (d. 395)\nBULLET::::- 889 – Abd-ar-Rahman III, first Caliph of Córdoba (d. 961)\nBULLET::::- 1113 – Wang Chongyang, Chinese religious leader and poet (d. 1170)\nBULLET::::- 1209 – Möngke Khan, Mongolian emperor (d. 1259)\nBULLET::::- 1322 – Emperor Kōmyō of Japan (d. 1380)\nBULLET::::- 1359 – Emperor Go-En'yū of Japan (d. 1393)\nBULLET::::- 1395 – Michele of Valois, daughter of Charles VI of France (d. 1422)\nBULLET::::- 1503 – Parmigianino, Italian artist (d. 1540)\nBULLET::::- 1589 – William Strode, English politician (d. 1666)\nBULLET::::- 1591 – Robert Devereux, 3rd Earl of Essex, English general and politician, Lord Lieutenant of Staffordshire (d. 1646)\nBULLET::::- 1624 – Bastiaan Govertsz van der Leeuw, Dutch painter (d. 1680)\nBULLET::::- 1630 – John Rogers, English-American minister, physician