{"id": "15849", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15849", "title": "July 4", "text": "July 4\n\nBULLET::::- 362 BC – Battle of Mantinea: The Thebans, led by Epaminondas, defeated the Spartans.\nBULLET::::- 414 – Emperor Theodosius II, age 13, yields power to his older sister Aelia Pulcheria, who reigned as regent and proclaimed herself empress (\"Augusta\") of the Eastern Roman Empire.\nBULLET::::- 836 – \"Pactum Sicardi\", a peace treaty between the Principality of Benevento and the Duchy of Naples, is signed.\nBULLET::::- 993 – Ulrich of Augsburg is canonized as a saint.\nBULLET::::- 1054 – A supernova, called SN 1054, is seen by Chinese Song dynasty, Arab, and possibly Amerindian observers near the star Zeta Tauri. For several months it remains bright enough to be seen during the day. Its remnants form the Crab Nebula.\nBULLET::::- 1120 – Jordan II of Capua is anointed as prince after his infant nephew's death.\nBULLET::::- 1187 – The Crusades: Battle of Hattin: Saladin defeats Guy of Lusignan, King of Jerusalem.\nBULLET::::- 1253 – Battle of West-Capelle: John I of Avesnes defeats Guy of Dampierre.\nBULLET::::- 1359 – Francesco II Ordelaffi of Forlì surrenders to the Papal commander Gil de Albornoz.\nBULLET::::- 1456 – Ottoman–Hungarian wars: The Siege of Nándorfehérvár (Belgrade) begins.\nBULLET::::- 1534 – Christian III is elected King of Denmark and Norway in the town of Rye.\nBULLET::::- 1584 – Philip Amadas and Arthur Barlowe arrive at Roanoke Island\nBULLET::::- 1610 – The Battle of Klushino is fought between forces of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth and Russia during the Polish–Muscovite War.\nBULLET::::- 1634 – The city of Trois-Rivières is founded in New France (now Quebec, Canada).\nBULLET::::- 1744 – The Treaty of Lancaster, in which the Iroquois cede lands between the Allegheny Mountains and the Ohio River to the British colonies, was signed in Lancaster, Pennsylvania.\nBULLET::::- 1774 – Orangetown Resolutions are adopted in the Province of New York, one of many protests against the British Parliament's Coercive Acts.\nBULLET::::- 1776 – American Revolution: The United States Declaration of Independence is adopted by the Second Continental Congress.\nBULLET::::- 1778 – American Revolutionary War: U.S. forces under George Clark capture Kaskaskia during the Illinois campaign.\nBULLET::::- 1802 – At West Point, New York, the United States Military Academy opens.\nBULLET::::- 1803 – The Louisiana Purchase is announced to the U.S. people.\nBULLET::::- 1817 – In Rome, New York, construction on the Erie Canal begins.\nBULLET::::- 1826 – Thomas Jefferson, third president of the United States, dies the same day as John Adams, second president of the United States, on the fiftieth anniversary of the adoption of the United States Declaration of Independence.\nBULLET::::- 1827 – Slavery is abolished in the State of New York.\nBULLET::::- 1831 – Samuel Francis Smith writes \"My Country, 'Tis of Thee\" for the Boston, Massachusetts July 4 festivities.\nBULLET::::- 1837 – Grand Junction Railway, the world's first long-distance railway, opens between Birmingham and Liverpool.\nBULLET::::- 1838 – The Iowa Territory is organized.\nBULLET::::- 1845 – Henry David Thoreau moves into a small cabin on Walden Pond in Concord, Massachusetts. Thoreau's account of his two years there, \"Walden\", will become a touchstone of the environmental movement.\nBULLET::::- 1855 – The first edition of Walt Whitman's book of poems, \"Leaves of Grass\", is published In Brooklyn.\nBULLET::::- 1862 – Lewis Carroll tells Alice Liddell a story that would grow into \"Alice's Adventures in Wonderland\" and its sequels.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: Siege of Vicksburg: Vicksburg, Mississippi surrenders to U.S. forces under Ulysses S. Grant after 47 days of siege. One hundred fifty miles up the Mississippi River, a Confederate army is repulsed at the Battle of Helena, Arkansas.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: The Army of Northern Virginia withdraws from the battlefield after losing the Battle of Gettysburg, signalling an end to the Confederate invasion of U.S. territory.\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Anglo-Zulu War: The Zululand capital of Ulundi is captured by British troops and burned to the ground, ending the war and forcing King Cetshwayo to flee.\nBULLET::::- 1881 – In Alabama, the Tuskegee Institute opens.\nBULLET::::- 1886 – The first scheduled Canadian transcontinental train arrives in Port Moody, British Columbia.\nBULLET::::- 1887 – The founder of Pakistan, Quaid-i-Azam Muhammad Ali Jinnah, joins Sindh-Madrasa-tul-Islam, Karachi.\nBULLET::::- 1892 – Western Samoa changes the International Date Line, causing Monday (July 4) to occur twice, resulting in a year with 367 days.\nBULLET::::- 1892 – The first double-decked street car service was inaugurated in San Diego, California.\nBULLET::::- 1894 – The short-lived Republic of Hawaii is proclaimed by Sanford B. Dole.\nBULLET::::- 1898 – En route from New York to Le Havre, the SS \"La Bourgogne\" collides with another ship and sinks off the coast of Sable Island, with the loss of 549 lives.\nBULLET::::- 1901 – William Howard Taft becomes American governor of the Philippines.\nBULLET::::- 1903 – The Philippine–American War is officially concluded.\nBULLET::::- 1910 – African-American boxer Jack Johnson knocks out white boxer Jim Jeffries in a heavyweight boxing match, sparking race riots across the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1911 – A massive heat wave strikes the northeastern United States, killing 380 people in eleven days and breaking temperature records in several cities.\nBULLET::::- 1913 – President Woodrow Wilson addresses American Civil War veterans at the Great Reunion of 1913.\nBULLET::::- 1914 – The funeral of Archduke Franz Ferdinand and his wife Sophie takes place in Vienna, six days after their assassinations in Sarajevo.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Mehmed V died at the age of 73 and Ottoman sultan Mehmed VI ascends to the throne.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – World War I: The Battle of Hamel, a successful attack by the Australian Corps against German positions near the town of Le Hamel on the Western Front.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Bolsheviks kill Tsar Nicholas II of Russia and his family (Julian calendar date).\nBULLET::::- 1927 – First flight of the Lockheed Vega.\nBULLET::::- 1934 – Leo Szilard patents the chain-reaction design that would later be used in the atomic bomb.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – Lou Gehrig, recently diagnosed with Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, informs a crowd at Yankee Stadium that he considers himself \"The luckiest man on the face of the earth\", then announces his retirement from major league baseball.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – Nazi crimes against the Polish nation: Nazi troops massacre Polish scientists and writers in the captured Ukrainian city of Lviv.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: The Burning of the Riga synagogues: The Great Choral Synagogue in German occupied Riga is burnt with 300 Jews locked in the basement.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: The 250-day Siege of Sevastopol in the Crimea ends when the city falls to Axis forces.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: The Battle of Kursk, the largest full-scale battle in history and the world's largest tank battle, begins in the village of Prokhorovka.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: In Gibraltar, a Royal Air Force B-24 Liberator bomber crashes into the sea in an apparent accident moments after takeoff, killing sixteen passengers on board, including general Władysław Sikorski, the commander-in-chief of the Polish Army and the Prime Minister of the Polish government-in-exile; only the pilot survives.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – The Kielce pogrom against Jewish Holocaust survivors in Poland.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – After 381 years of near-continuous colonial rule by various powers, the Philippines attains full independence from the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – The \"Indian Independence Bill\" is presented before the British House of Commons, proposing the independence of the Provinces of British India into two sovereign countries: India and Pakistan.\nBULLET::::- 1950 – Cold War: Radio Free Europe first broadcasts.\nBULLET::::- 1951 – Cold War: A court in Czechoslovakia sentences American journalist William N. Oatis to ten years in prison on charges of espionage.\nBULLET::::- 1951 – William Shockley announces the invention of the junction transistor.\nBULLET::::- 1958 – U.S. President Dwight D. Eisenhower signed the Rivers and Harbors Flood Control Bill.\nBULLET::::- 1960 – Due to the post-Independence Day admission of Hawaii as the 50th U.S. state on August 21, 1959, the 50-star flag of the United States debuts in Philadelphia, almost ten and a half months later (see Flag Acts (United States)).\nBULLET::::- 1961 – On its maiden voyage, the Soviet nuclear-powered submarine \"K-19\" suffers a complete loss of coolant to its reactor. The crew are able to effect repairs, but 22 of them die of radiation poisoning over the following two years.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – U.S. President Lyndon B. Johnson signs the Freedom of Information Act into United States law. The act went into effect the next year.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – Israeli commandos raid Entebbe airport in Uganda, rescuing all but four of the passengers and crew of an Air France jetliner seized by Palestinian terrorists.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – The U.S. celebrates its Bicentennial.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – The George Jackson Brigade plants a bomb at the main power substation for the Washington state capitol in Olympia, in solidarity with a prison strike at the Walla Walla State Penitentiary Intensive Security Unit.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – Three Iranian diplomats and a journalist are kidnapped in Lebanon by Phalange forces, and their fate remains unknown.\nBULLET::::- 1987 – In France, former Gestapo chief Klaus Barbie (a.k.a. the \"Butcher of Lyon\") is convicted of crimes against humanity and sentenced to life imprisonment.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – Rwandan genocide: Kigali, the Rwandan capital, is captured by the Rwandan Patriotic Front, ending the genocide in the city.\nBULLET::::- 1997 – NASA's Pathfinder space probe lands on the surface of Mars.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – Japan launches the Nozomi probe to Mars, joining the United States and Russia as a space exploring nation.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – Vladivostock Air Flight 352 crashes on approach to Irkutsk Airport killing all 145 people on board.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The cornerstone of the Freedom Tower is laid on the World Trade Center site in New York City.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – Greece beats Portugal in the UEFA Euro 2004 Final and becomes European Champion for first time in its history.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – The Deep Impact collider hits the comet Tempel 1.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – The Statue of Liberty's crown reopens to the public after eight years of closure due to security concerns following the September 11 attacks.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – The first of four days of bombings begins on the southern Philippine island group of Mindanao.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – The discovery of particles consistent with the Higgs boson at the Large Hadron Collider is announced at CERN.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – Chile claims its first title in international soccer by defeating Argentina in the 2015 Copa América Final.\n\nBULLET::::- AD 68 – Salonina Matidia, Roman daughter of Ulpia Marciana (d. 119)\nBULLET::::- 1095 – Usama ibn Munqidh, Muslim poet, author and faris (Knight) (d. 1188)\nBULLET::::- 1330 – Ashikaga Yoshiakira, Japanese shōgun (d. 1367)\nBULLET::::- 1477 – Johannes Aventinus, Bavarian historian and philologist (d. 1534)\nBULLET::::- 1546 – Murad III, Ottoman sultan (d. 1595)\nBULLET::::- 1656 – John Leake, Royal Navy admiral (d. 1720)\nBULLET::::- 1694 – Louis-Claude Daquin, French organist and composer (d. 1772)\nBULLET::::- 1715 – Christian Fürchtegott Gellert, German poet and academic (d. 1769)\nBULLET::::- 1719 – Michel-Jean Sedaine, French playwright (d. 1797)\nBULLET::::- 1729 – George Leonard, American lawyer, jurist and politician (d. 1819)\nBULLET::::- 1753 – Jean-Pierre Blanchard, French inventor, best known as a pioneer in balloon flight (d. 1809)\nBULLET::::- 1790 – George Everest, Welsh geographer and surveyor (d. 1866)\nBULLET::::- 1799 – Oscar I of Sweden (d. 1859)\nBULLET::::- 1804 – Nathaniel Hawthorne, American novelist and short story writer (d. 1864)\nBULLET::::- 1807 – Giuseppe Garibaldi, Italian general and politician (d. 1882)\nBULLET::::- 1816 – Hiram Walker, American businessman, founded Canadian Club whisky (d. 1899)\nBULLET::::- 1826 – Stephen Foster, American songwriter and composer (d. 1864)\nBULLET::::- 1842 – Hermann Cohen, German philosopher (d. 1918)\nBULLET::::- 1845 – Thomas John Barnardo, Irish philanthropist and humanitarian (d. 1905)\nBULLET::::- 1847 – James Anthony Bailey, American circus ringmaster, co-founded Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus (d. 1906)\nBULLET::::- 1854 – Victor Babeș, Romanian physician and biologist (d. 1926)\nBULLET::::- 1868 – Henrietta Swan Leavitt, American astronomer and academic (d. 1921)\nBULLET::::- 1871 – Hubert Cecil Booth, English engineer (d.1955)\nBULLET::::- 1872 – Calvin Coolidge, American lawyer and politician, 30th President of the United States (d. 1933)\nBULLET::::- 1874 – John McPhee, Australian journalist and politician, 27th Premier of Tasmania (d. 1952)\nBULLET::::- 1880 – Victor Kraft, Austrian philosopher from the Vienna Circle (d. 1975)\nBULLET::::- 1881 – Ulysses S. Grant III, American general (d. 1968)\nBULLET::::- 1883 – Rube Goldberg, American sculptor, cartoonist, and engineer (d. 1970)\nBULLET::::- 1887 – Pio Pion, Italian engineer and businessman (d. 1965)\nBULLET::::- 1888 – Henry Armetta, Italian-American actor and singer (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1895 – Irving Caesar, American songwriter and composer (d. 1996)\nBULLET::::- 1896 – Mao Dun, Chinese journalist, author, and critic (d. 1981)\nBULLET::::- 1897 – Alluri Sitarama Raju, Indian activist (d. 1924)\nBULLET::::- 1898 – Pilar Barbosa, Puerto Rican-American historian and activist (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1898 – Gertrude Lawrence, British actress, singer, and dancer (d. 1952)\nBULLET::::- 1898 – Gulzarilal Nanda, Indian politician (d. 1998)\nBULLET::::- 1898 – Gertrude Weaver, American supercentenarian (d. 2015)\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Belinda Dann, Indigenous Australian who was one of the Stolen Generation, reunited with family aged 107 (d. 2007)\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Nellie Mae Rowe, African-American folk artist (d. 1982)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Meyer Lansky, American gangster (d. 1983)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – George Murphy, American actor and politician (d. 1992)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Flor Peeters, Belgian organist, composer, and educator (d. 1986)\nBULLET::::- 1904 – Angela Baddeley, English actress (d. 1976)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – Irving Johnson, American sailor and author (d. 1991)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – Robert Hankey, 2nd Baron Hankey, British diplomat and public servant (d. 1996)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – Lionel Trilling, American critic, essayist, short story writer, and educator (d. 1975)\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Vincent Schaefer, American chemist and meteorologist (d. 1993)\nBULLET::::- 1907 – John Anderson, American discus thrower (d. 1948)\nBULLET::::- 1907 – Howard Taubman, American author and critic (d. 1996)\nBULLET::::- 1909 – Alec Templeton, Welsh composer, pianist and satirist (d. 1963)\nBULLET::::- 1910 – Robert K. Merton, American sociologist and scholar (d. 2003)\nBULLET::::- 1910 – Gloria Stuart, American actress (d. 2010)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Bruce Hamilton, Australian public servant (d. 1989)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Mitch Miller, American singer and producer (d. 2010)\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Nuccio Bertone, Italian automobile designer (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1915 – Timmie Rogers, American actor and singer-songwriter (d. 2006)\nBULLET::::- 1916 – Iva Toguri D'Aquino, American typist and broadcaster (d. 2006)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Eppie Lederer, American journalist and radio host (d. 2002)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Johnnie Parsons, American race car driver (d. 1984)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – King Taufa'ahau Tupou IV of Tonga, (d. 2006)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Alec Bedser, English cricketer (d. 2010)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Eric Bedser, English cricketer (d. 2006)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Pauline Phillips, American journalist and radio host, created Dear Abby (d. 2013)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – Norm Drucker, American basketball player and referee (d. 2015)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – Leona Helmsley, American businesswoman (d. 2007)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – Fritz Wilde, German footballer and manager (d. 1977)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – Paul Bannai, American politician\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Gérard Debreu, French economist and mathematician, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 2004)\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Nasser Sharifi, Iranian sports shooter\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Metropolitan Mikhail of Asyut (d. 2014)\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Philip Rose, American actor, playwright, and producer (d. 2011)\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Tibor Varga, Hungarian violinist and conductor (d. 2003)\nBULLET::::- 1922 – R. James Harvey, American politician\nBULLET::::- 1923 – Rudolf Friedrich, Swiss lawyer and politician (d. 2013)\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Eva Marie Saint, American actress\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Delia Fiallo, Cuban author and screenwriter\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Ciril Zlobec, Slovene poet, writer, translator, journalist and politician (d. 2018)\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Dorothy Head Knode, American tennis player (d. 2015)\nBULLET::::- 1926 – Alfredo Di Stéfano, Argentinian-Spanish footballer and coach (d. 2014)\nBULLET::::- 1926 – Lake Underwood, American race car driver and businessman (d. 2008)\nBULLET::::- 1927 – Gina Lollobrigida, Italian actress and photographer\nBULLET::::- 1927 – Neil Simon, American playwright and screenwriter (d. 2018)\nBULLET::::- 1928 – Giampiero Boniperti, Italian footballer and politician\nBULLET::::- 1928 – Teofisto Guingona Jr., Filipino politician; 11th Vice President of the Philippines\nBULLET::::- 1928 – Jassem Alwan, Syrian Army Officer (d. 2018)\nBULLET