{"id": "15854", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15854", "title": "June 3", "text": "June 3\n\nBULLET::::- 350 – The Roman usurper Nepotianus, of the Constantinian dynasty, proclaims himself Roman emperor, entering Rome at the head of a group of gladiators.\nBULLET::::- 713 – The Byzantine emperor Philippicus is blinded, deposed and sent into exile by conspirators of the Opsikion army in Thrace. He is succeeded by Anastasios II, who begins the reorganization of the Byzantine army.\nBULLET::::- 1140 – The French scholar Peter Abelard is found guilty of heresy.\nBULLET::::- 1326 – The Treaty of Novgorod delineates borders between Russia and Norway in Finnmark.\nBULLET::::- 1539 – Hernando de Soto claims Florida for Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1608 – Samuel de Champlain completes his third voyage to New France at Tadoussac, Quebec.\nBULLET::::- 1621 – The Dutch West India Company receives a charter for New Netherland.\nBULLET::::- 1658 – Pope Alexander VII appoints François de Laval vicar apostolic in New France.\nBULLET::::- 1665 – James Stuart, Duke of York (later to become King James II of England), defeats the Dutch fleet off the coast of Lowestoft.\nBULLET::::- 1781 – Jack Jouett begins his midnight ride to warn Thomas Jefferson and the Virginia legislature of an impending raid by Banastre Tarleton.\nBULLET::::- 1839 – In Humen, China, Lin Tse-hsü destroys 1.2 million kilograms of opium confiscated from British merchants, providing Britain with a \"casus belli\" to open hostilities, resulting in the First Opium War.\nBULLET::::- 1861 – American Civil War: Battle of Philippi (also called the Philippi Races): Union forces rout Confederate troops in Barbour County, Virginia, now West Virginia.\nBULLET::::- 1864 – American Civil War: Battle of Cold Harbor: Union forces attack Confederate troops in Hanover County, Virginia.\nBULLET::::- 1866 – The Fenians are driven out of Fort Erie, Ontario back into the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1885 – In the last military engagement fought on Canadian soil, the Cree leader, Big Bear, escapes the North-West Mounted Police.\nBULLET::::- 1889 – The first long-distance electric power transmission line in the United States is completed, running between a generator at Willamette Falls and downtown Portland, Oregon.\nBULLET::::- 1916 – The National Defense Act is signed into law, increasing the size of the United States National Guard by 450,000 men.\nBULLET::::- 1935 – One thousand unemployed Canadian workers board freight cars in Vancouver, beginning a protest trek to Ottawa.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – The Duke of Windsor marries Wallis Simpson.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – World War II: The Luftwaffe bombs Paris.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – World War II: The Battle of Dunkirk ends with a German victory and with Allied forces in full retreat.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – Franz Rademacher proposes plans to make Madagascar the \"Jewish homeland\", an idea that had first been considered by 19th century journalist Theodor Herzl.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: The Wehrmacht razes the Greek village of Kandanos to the ground and murders 180 of its inhabitants.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: Japan begins the Aleutian Islands Campaign by bombing Unalaska Island.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – In Los Angeles, California, white U.S. Navy sailors and Marines clash with Latino youths in the Zoot Suit Riots.\nBULLET::::- 1950 – Herzog and Lachenal of the French Annapurna expedition become the first climbers to reach the summit of an 8,000-metre peak.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – At Paris Orly Airport, Air France Flight 007 overruns the runway and explodes when the crew attempts to abort takeoff, killing 130.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – The Buddhist crisis: Soldiers of the Army of the Republic of Vietnam attack protesting Buddhists in Huế, South Vietnam, with liquid chemicals from tear-gas grenades, causing 67 people to be hospitalised for blistering of the skin and respiratory ailments.\nBULLET::::- 1965 – The launch of \"Gemini 4\", the first multi-day space mission by a NASA crew. Ed White, a crew member, performs the first American spacewalk.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – Melbourne–Evans collision: off the coast of South Vietnam, the Australian aircraft carrier cuts the U.S. Navy destroyer in half.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – A Soviet supersonic Tupolev Tu-144 crashes near Goussainville, France, killing 14, the first crash of a supersonic passenger aircraft.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – A blowout at the Ixtoc I oil well in the southern Gulf of Mexico causes at least of oil to be spilled into the waters, the second-worst accidental oil spill ever recorded.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – An explosive device is detonated at the Statue of Liberty. The FBI suspects Croatian nationalists.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – The 1980 Grand Island tornado outbreak hits Nebraska, causing five deaths and $300 million (equivalent to $ million in ) worth of damage.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – The Israeli ambassador to the United Kingdom, Shlomo Argov, is shot on a London street; he survives but is left paralysed.\nBULLET::::- 1984 – Operation Blue Star, a military offensive, is launched by the Indian government at Harmandir Sahib, also known as the Golden Temple, the holiest shrine for Sikhs, in Amritsar. The operation continues until June 6, with casualties, most of them civilians, in excess of 5,000.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – The government of China sends troops to force protesters out of Tiananmen Square after seven weeks of occupation.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Mount Unzen erupts in Kyūshū, Japan, killing 43 people, all of them either researchers or journalists.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – Aboriginal land rights are granted in Australia in Mabo v Queensland (No 2), a case brought by Eddie Mabo.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – After suffering a mechanical failure, a high speed train derails at Eschede, Germany, killing 101 people.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – The union of Serbia and Montenegro comes to an end with Montenegro's formal declaration of independence.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – A plane carrying 153 people on board crashes in a residential neighborhood in Lagos, Nigeria, killing everyone on board and 10 people on the ground.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – The pageant for the Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II takes place on the River Thames.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – The trial of United States Army private Chelsea Manning for leaking classified material to WikiLeaks begins in Fort Meade, Maryland.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – At least 119 people are killed in a fire at a poultry farm in Jilin Province in northeastern China.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – An explosion at a gasoline station in Accra, Ghana, killing more than 200 people.\nBULLET::::- 2017 – London Bridge attack: Eight people are murdered and dozens of civilians are wounded by Islamist terrorists. Three of the attackers are shot dead by the police.\nBULLET::::- 2019 – Khartoum massacre: In Sudan, over 100 people are killed when security forces accompanied by Janjaweed militiamen storm and open fire on a sit-in protest.\n\nBULLET::::- 20 BC – Sejanus, Roman soldier and bodyguard (d. 31 AD)\nBULLET::::- 1139 – Conon of Naso, Basilian abbot (d. 1236)\nBULLET::::- 1421 – Giovanni di Cosimo de' Medici, Italian noble (d. 1463)\nBULLET::::- 1454 – Bogislaw X, Duke of Pomerania (1474–1523) (d. 1523)\nBULLET::::- 1537 – João Manuel, Prince of Portugal (d. 1554)\nBULLET::::- 1540 – Charles II, Archduke of Austria (d. 1590)\nBULLET::::- 1554 – Pietro de' Medici, Italian noble (d. 1604)\nBULLET::::- 1594 – César, Duke of Vendôme, French nobleman (d. 1665)\nBULLET::::- 1603 – Pietro Paolini, Italian painter (d. 1681)\nBULLET::::- 1635 – Philippe Quinault, French playwright and composer (d. 1688)\nBULLET::::- 1636 – John Hale, American minister (d. 1700)\nBULLET::::- 1659 – David Gregory, Scottish-English mathematician and astronomer (d. 1708)\nBULLET::::- 1662 – Willem van Mieris, Dutch painter (d. 1747)\nBULLET::::- 1723 – Giovanni Antonio Scopoli, Italian physician, geologist, and botanist (d. 1788)\nBULLET::::- 1726 – James Hutton, Scottish geologist and physician (d. 1797)\nBULLET::::- 1736 – Ignaz Fränzl, German violinist and composer (d. 1811)\nBULLET::::- 1770 – Manuel Belgrano, Argentinian economist, lawyer, and politician (d. 1820)\nBULLET::::- 1808 – Jefferson Davis, American colonel and politician, President of the Confederate States of America (d. 1889)\nBULLET::::- 1818 – Louis Faidherbe, French general and politician, Governor of Senegal (d. 1889)\nBULLET::::- 1819 – Anton Anderledy, Swiss religious leader, 23rd Superior General of the Society of Jesus (d. 1892)\nBULLET::::- 1819 – Johan Jongkind, Dutch painter (d. 1891)\nBULLET::::- 1832 – Charles Lecocq, French pianist and composer (d. 1918)\nBULLET::::- 1843 – Frederick VIII of Denmark (d. 1912)\nBULLET::::- 1844 – Garret Hobart, American lawyer and politician, 24th Vice President of the United States (d. 1899)\nBULLET::::- 1844 – Detlev von Liliencron, German poet and author (d. 1909)\nBULLET::::- 1852 – Theodore Robinson, American painter and academic (d. 1896)\nBULLET::::- 1853 – Flinders Petrie, English archaeologist and academic (d. 1942)\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Otto Erich Hartleben, German poet and playwright (d. 1905)\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Ransom E. Olds, American businessman, founded Oldsmobile and REO Motor Car Company (d. 1950)\nBULLET::::- 1865 – George V of the United Kingdom (d. 1936)\nBULLET::::- 1866 – George Howells Broadhurst, English-American director and manager (d. 1952)\nBULLET::::- 1873 – Otto Loewi, German-American pharmacologist and psychobiologist, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1961)\nBULLET::::- 1877 – Raoul Dufy, French painter and illustrator (d. 1953)\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Alla Nazimova, Ukrainian-American actress, producer, and screenwriter (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Raymond Pearl, American biologist and botanist (d. 1940)\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Vivian Woodward, English footballer and soldier (d. 1954)\nBULLET::::- 1881 – Mikhail Larionov, Russian painter and set designer (d. 1964)\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Baburao Painter, Indian actor, director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 1954)\nBULLET::::- 1897 – Memphis Minnie, American singer-songwriter (d. 1973)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Georg von Békésy, Hungarian-American biophysicist and academic, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1972)\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Adelaide Ames, American astronomer and academic (d. 1932)\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Leo Picard, German-Israeli geologist and academic (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1901 – Maurice Evans, English actor (d. 1989)\nBULLET::::- 1901 – Zhang Xueliang, Chinese general and warlord (d. 2001)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Eddie Acuff, American actor (d. 1956)\nBULLET::::- 1904 – Charles R. Drew, American physician and surgeon (d. 1950)\nBULLET::::- 1904 – Jan Peerce, American tenor and actor (d. 1984)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – Martin Gottfried Weiss, German SS officer (d. 1946)\nBULLET::::- 1906 – R. G. D. Allen, English economist, mathematician, and statistician (d. 1983)\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Josephine Baker, French actress, singer, and dancer; French Resistance operative (d. 1975)\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Walter Robins, English cricketer and footballer (d. 1968)\nBULLET::::- 1907 – Paul Rotha, English director and producer (d. 1984)\nBULLET::::- 1910 – Paulette Goddard, American actress and model (d. 1990)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Ellen Corby, American actress and screenwriter (d. 1999)\nBULLET::::- 1913 – Pedro Mir, Dominican poet and author (d. 2000)\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Ignacio Ponseti, Spanish physician and orthopedist (d. 2009)\nBULLET::::- 1917 – Leo Gorcey, American actor (d. 1969)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Patrick Cargill, English actor and producer (d. 1996)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Lili St. Cyr, American dancer (d. 1999)\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Forbes Carlile, Australian pentathlete and coach (d. 2016)\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Jean Dréjac, French singer and composer (d. 2003)\nBULLET::::- 1922 – Alain Resnais, French director, cinematographer, and screenwriter (d. 2014)\nBULLET::::- 1923 – Igor Shafarevich, Russian mathematician and theorist (d. 2017)\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Karunanidhi, Indian screenwriter and politician, 3rd Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu (d. 2018)\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Colleen Dewhurst, Canadian-American actress (d. 1991)\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Bernard Glasser, American director and producer (d. 2014)\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Jimmy Rogers, American singer and guitarist (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Torsten Wiesel, Swedish neurophysiologist and academic, Nobel Prize laureate\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Tony Curtis, American actor (d. 2010)\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Thomas Winning, Scottish cardinal (d. 2001)\nBULLET::::- 1926 – Allen Ginsberg, American poet (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1926 – Flora MacDonald, Canadian banker and politician, 10th Canadian Minister of Communications (d. 2015)\nBULLET::::- 1927 – Boots Randolph, American saxophonist and composer (d. 2007)\nBULLET::::- 1928 – Donald Judd, American sculptor and painter (d. 1994)\nBULLET::::- 1928 – John Richard Reid, New Zealand cricketer\nBULLET::::- 1929 – Werner Arber, Swiss microbiologist and geneticist, Nobel Prize laureate\nBULLET::::- 1929 – Chuck Barris, American game show host and producer (d. 2017)\nBULLET::::- 1930 – Marion Zimmer Bradley, American author and poet (d. 1999)\nBULLET::::- 1930 – George Fernandes, Indian journalist and politician, Minister of Defence for India\nBULLET::::- 1930 – Dakota Staton, American singer (d. 2007)\nBULLET::::- 1930 – Abbas Zandi, Iranian wrestler (d. 2017)\nBULLET::::- 1930 – Ben Wada, Japanese director and producer (d. 2011)\nBULLET::::- 1931 – Françoise Arnoul, Algerian-French actress\nBULLET::::- 1931 – Raúl Castro, Cuban commander and politician, 18th President of Cuba\nBULLET::::- 1931 – John Norman, American philosopher and author\nBULLET::::- 1931 – Lindy Remigino, American runner and coach\nBULLET::::- 1933 – Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa, Bahranian king (d. 1999)\nBULLET::::- 1936 – Larry McMurtry, American novelist and screenwriter\nBULLET::::- 1936 – Colin Meads, New Zealand rugby player and coach (d. 2017)\nBULLET::::- 1937 – Jean-Pierre Jaussaud, French 