{"id": "15862", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15862", "title": "July 6", "text": "July 6\n\nBULLET::::- 371 BC – The Battle of Leuctra, where Epaminondas defeated Cleombrotus I, takes place.Charlie Austin\nBULLET::::- 640 – Battle of Heliopolis: The Muslim Arab army under 'Amr ibn al-'As defeat the Byzantine forces near Heliopolis (Egypt).\nBULLET::::- 1253 – Mindaugas is crowned King of Lithuania.\nBULLET::::- 1348 – Pope Clement VI issues a papal bull protecting the Jews accused of having caused the Black Death.\nBULLET::::- 1411 – Ming China's Admiral Zheng He returns to Nanjing after the third treasure voyage and presents the Sinhalese king, captured during the Ming–Kotte War, to the Yongle Emperor.\nBULLET::::- 1415 – Jan Hus is condemned by the assembly of the Council in the Cathedral as a heretic and sentenced to be burned at the stake. (See Deaths section.)\nBULLET::::- 1438 – A temporary compromise between the rebellious Transylvanian peasants and the noblemen is signed in Kolozsmonostor Abbey.\nBULLET::::- 1483 – Richard III is crowned King of England.\nBULLET::::- 1484 – Portuguese sea captain Diogo Cão finds the mouth of the Congo River.\nBULLET::::- 1495 – First Italian War: Battle of Fornovo: Charles VIII defeats the Holy League.\nBULLET::::- 1535 – Sir Thomas More is executed for treason against King Henry VIII of England.\nBULLET::::- 1557 – King Philip II of Spain, consort of Queen Mary I of England, sets out from Dover to war with France, which eventually resulted in the loss of the City of Calais, the last English possession on the continent, and Mary I never seeing her husband again.\nBULLET::::- 1560 – The Treaty of Edinburgh is signed by Scotland and England.\nBULLET::::- 1573 – Córdoba, Argentina, is founded by Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera.\nBULLET::::- 1573 – French Wars of Religion: Siege of La Rochelle ends.\nBULLET::::- 1614 – Żejtun and the surrounding villages suffer a raid from Ottoman forces. This was the last unsuccessful attempt by the Ottomans to conquer the island of Malta.\nBULLET::::- 1630 – Thirty Years' War: Four thousand Swedish troops under Gustavus Adolphus land in Pomerania, Germany.\nBULLET::::- 1685 – Battle of Sedgemoor: Last battle of the Monmouth Rebellion. troops of King James II defeat troops of James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth.\nBULLET::::- 1751 – Pope Benedict XIV suppresses the Patriarchate of Aquileia and establishes from its territory the Archdiocese of Udine and Gorizia.\nBULLET::::- 1777 – American Revolutionary War: Siege of Fort Ticonderoga: After a bombardment by British artillery under General John Burgoyne, American forces retreat from Fort Ticonderoga, New York.\nBULLET::::- 1779 – Battle of Grenada: The French defeat British naval forces during the American Revolutionary War.\nBULLET::::- 1801 – First Battle of Algeciras: Outnumbered French Navy ships defeat the Royal Navy in the fortified Spanish port of Algeciras.\nBULLET::::- 1809 – The second day of the Battle of Wagram; France defeats the Austrian army in the largest battle to date of the Napoleonic Wars.\nBULLET::::- 1854 – In Jackson, Michigan, the first convention of the United States Republican Party is held.\nBULLET::::- 1865 – The first issue of \"The Nation\" magazine is published.\nBULLET::::- 1885 – Louis Pasteur successfully tests his vaccine against rabies on Joseph Meister, a boy who was bitten by a rabid dog.\nBULLET::::- 1887 – David Kalākaua, monarch of the Kingdom of Hawaii, is forced to sign the Bayonet Constitution, which transfers much of the king's authority to the Legislature of the Kingdom of Hawaii.\nBULLET::::- 1892 – Three thousand eight hundred striking steelworkers engage in a day-long battle with Pinkerton agents during the Homestead Strike, leaving ten dead and dozens wounded.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – World War I: Arabian troops led by T. E. Lawrence (\"Lawrence of Arabia\") and Auda ibu Tayi capture Aqaba from the Ottoman Empire during the Arab Revolt.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – The Left SR uprising in Russia starts with the assassination of German ambassador Wilhelm von Mirbach by Cheka members.\nBULLET::::- 1919 – The British dirigible R34 lands in New York, completing the first crossing of the Atlantic Ocean by an airship.\nBULLET::::- 1933 – The first Major League Baseball All-Star Game is played in Chicago's Comiskey Park. The American League defeated the National League 4–2.\nBULLET::::- 1936 – A major breach of the Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal in England sends millions of gallons of water cascading into the River Irwell.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – Spanish Civil War: Battle of Brunete: The battle begins with Spanish Republican troops going on the offensive against the Nationalists to relieve pressure on Madrid.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – Anti-Jewish legislation in prewar Nazi Germany closes the last remaining Jewish enterprises.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – Story Bridge, a major landmark in Brisbane, as well as Australia's longest cantilever bridge is formally opened.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – The German army launches its offensive to encircle several Soviet armies near Smolensk.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – Anne Frank and her family go into hiding in the \"Secret Annexe\" above her father's office in an Amsterdam warehouse.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – Jackie Robinson refuses to move to the back of a bus, leading to a court-martial.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – The Hartford circus fire, one of America's worst fire disasters, kills approximately 168 people and injures over 700 in Hartford, Connecticut.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Referendum held in Sylhet to decide its fate in the Partition of India.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – The AK-47 goes into production in the Soviet Union.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – Althea Gibson wins the Wimbledon championships, becoming the first black athlete to do so.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – John Lennon and Paul McCartney meet for the first time, as teenagers at Woolton Fete, three years before forming the Beatles.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – As a part of Operation Plowshare, the Sedan nuclear test takes place.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – \"The Late Late Show\", the world's longest-running chat show by the same broadcaster, airs on RTÉ One for the first time.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Malawi declares its independence from the United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – Malawi becomes a republic, with Hastings Banda as its first President.\nBULLET::::- 1967 – Nigerian Civil War: Nigerian forces invade Biafra, beginning the war.\nBULLET::::- 1975 – The Comoros declares independence from France.\nBULLET::::- 1986 – Davis Phinney becomes the first American cyclist to win a road stage of the Tour de France.\nBULLET::::- 1988 – The Piper Alpha drilling platform in the North Sea is destroyed by explosions and fires. One hundred sixty-seven oil workers are killed, making it the world's worst offshore oil disaster in terms of direct loss of life.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – The Tel Aviv–Jerusalem bus 405 suicide attack: Sixteen bus passengers are killed when a member of the Palestinian Islamic Jihad took control of the bus and drove it over a cliff.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – The Electronic Frontier Foundation is founded.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – In the Bosnian War, under the command of General Ratko Mladić, Serbia begins its attack on the Bosnian town of Srebrenica.\nBULLET::::- 1997 – The Troubles: In response to the Drumcree dispute, five days of mass protests, riots and gun battles begin in Irish nationalist districts of Northern Ireland.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – Hong Kong International Airport opens in Chek Lap Kok, Hong Kong, replacing Kai Tak Airport as the city's international airport.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – The 70-metre Yevpatoria Planetary Radar sends a METI message (Cosmic Call 2) to five stars: Hip 4872, HD 245409, 55 Cancri (HD 75732), HD 10307 and 47 Ursae Majoris (HD 95128). The messages will arrive to these stars in 2036, 2040, 2044, and 2049, respectively.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – The Nathu La pass between India and China, sealed during the Sino-Indian War, re-opens for trade after 44 years.\nBULLET::::