{"id": "15863", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15863", "title": "July 7", "text": "July 7\n\nThe terms 7th July, July 7th, and 7/7 (pronounced \"Seven-seven\") have been widely used in the Western media as a shorthand for the 7 July 2005 bombings on London's transport system. In the Chinese language, this term is used to denote the Battle of Lugou Bridge started on July 7, 1937, marking the beginning of the Second Sino-Japanese War.\n\nBULLET::::- 1124 – Tyre falls to the Crusaders.\nBULLET::::- 1456 – A retrial verdict acquits Joan of Arc of heresy 25 years after her death.\nBULLET::::- 1520 – Spanish \"conquistadores\" defeat a larger Aztec army at the Battle of Otumba.\nBULLET::::- 1534 – Jacques Cartier makes his first contact with aboriginal peoples in what is now Canada.\nBULLET::::- 1575 – The Raid of the Redeswire is the last major battle between England and Scotland.\nBULLET::::- 1585 – The Treaty of Nemours abolishes tolerance to Protestants in France.\nBULLET::::- 1770 – The Battle of Larga between the Russian Empire and the Ottoman Empire takes place.\nBULLET::::- 1777 – American forces retreating from Fort Ticonderoga are defeated in the Battle of Hubbardton.\nBULLET::::- 1798 – As a result of the XYZ Affair, the US Congress rescinds the Treaty of Alliance with France sparking the \"Quasi-War\".\nBULLET::::- 1807 – The Peace of Tilsit between France, Prussia and Russia ends the War of the Fourth Coalition.\nBULLET::::- 1834 – In New York City, four nights of rioting against abolitionists began.\nBULLET::::- 1846 – US troops occupy Monterey and Yerba Buena, thus beginning the US conquest of California.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – The United States begins its first military draft; exemptions cost $300.\nBULLET::::- 1865 – Four conspirators in the assassination of Abraham Lincoln are hanged.\nBULLET::::- 1892 – The Katipunan is established, the discovery of which by Spanish authorities initiated the Philippine Revolution.\nBULLET::::- 1898 – US President William McKinley signs the Newlands Resolution annexing Hawaii as a territory of the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1907 – Florenz Ziegfeld, Jr. staged his first Follies on the roof of the New York Theater in New York City.\nBULLET::::- 1911 – The United States, UK, Japan, and Russia sign the North Pacific Fur Seal Convention of 1911 banning open-water seal hunting, the first international treaty to address wildlife preservation issues.\nBULLET::::- 1915 – The First Battle of the Isonzo comes to an end.\nBULLET::::- 1915 – Colombo Town Guard officer Henry Pedris is executed in British Ceylon for allegedly inciting persecution of Muslims.\nBULLET::::- 1916 – The New Zealand Labour Party was founded in Wellington.\nBULLET::::- 1928 – Sliced bread is sold for the first time (on the inventor's 48th birthday) by the Chillicothe Baking Company of Chillicothe, Missouri.\nBULLET::::- 1930 – Industrialist Henry J. Kaiser begins construction of Boulder Dam (now known as Hoover Dam).\nBULLET::::- 1937 – The Marco Polo Bridge Incident provides the Imperial Japanese Army with a pretext for starting the Second Sino-Japanese War.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – The Peel Commission Report recommends the partition of Palestine, which was the first formal recommendation for partition in the history of Palestine.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – The US occupation of Iceland replaces the UK's occupation.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: Beirut is occupied by Free France and British troops.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: German submarine U-701 destroyed off Cape Hatteras.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – World War II: Largest Banzai charge of the Pacific War at the Battle of Saipan.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – Mother Francesca S. Cabrini becomes the first American to be canonized.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – Howard Hughes nearly dies when his XF-11 reconnaissance aircraft prototype crashes in a Beverly Hills neighborhood.\nBULLET::::- 1952 – The ocean liner passes Bishop Rock on her maiden voyage, breaking the transatlantic speed record to become the fastest passenger ship in the world.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – Ernesto \"Che\" Guevara sets out on a trip through Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador, Panama, Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras, and El Salvador.\nBULLET::::- 1954 – Elvis Presley makes his radio debut when WHBQ Memphis played his first recording for Sun Records, \"That's All Right\".\nBULLET::::- 1958 – US President Dwight D. Eisenhower signs the Alaska Statehood Act into law.\nBULLET::::- 1959 – Venus occults the star Regulus. This rare event is used to determine the diameter of Venus and the structure of the Venusian atmosphere.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Buddhist crisis: The police of Ngô Đình Nhu, brother and chief political adviser of President Ngô Đình Diệm, attacked a group of American journalists who were covering a protest.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – The Solomon Islands becomes independent from the United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – Institution of sharia law in Iran.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – During the Lebanese Civil War, 83 Tiger militants are killed during what will be known as the Safra massacre.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – US President Ronald Reagan appoints Sandra Day O'Connor to become the first female member of the Supreme Court of the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1983 – Cold War: Samantha Smith, a US schoolgirl, flies to the Soviet Union at the invitation of Secretary General Yuri Andropov.\nBULLET::::- 1985 – Boris Becker becomes the youngest player ever to win Wimbledon at age 17.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Yugoslav Wars: The Brioni Agreement ends the ten-day independence war in Slovenia against the rest of the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – The New York Court of Appeals rules that women have the same right as men to go topless in public.\nBULLET::::- 1997 – The Turkish Armed Forces withdraw from northern Iraq after assisting the Kurdistan Democratic Party in the Iraqi Kurdish Civil War.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – NASA Opportunity rover, MER-B or Mars Exploration Rover–B, was launched into space aboard a Delta II rocket.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – A series of four explosions occurs on London's transport system, killing 56 people, including four suicide bombers, and injuring over 700 others.\nBULLET::::- 2007 – The first Live Earth benefit concert was held in 11 locations around the world.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – At least 172 people are killed in a flash flood in the Krasnodar Krai region of Russia.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – A De Havilland Otter air taxi crashes in Soldotna, Alaska, killing ten people.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Ex-US Army soldier Micah Xavier Johnson shoots fourteen policemen during an anti-police protest in downtown Dallas, Texas, killing five of them. He is subsequently killed by a robot-delivered bomb.\n\nBULLET::::- 611 – Eudoxia Epiphania, daughter of Byzantine emperor Heraclius\nBULLET::::- 1053 – Emperor Shirakawa of Japan (d. 1129)\nBULLET::::- 1119 – Emperor Sutoku of Japan (d. 1164)\nBULLET::::- 1207 – Elizabeth of Hungary (d. 1231)\nBULLET::::- 1482 – Andrzej Krzycki, Polish archbishop (d. 1537)\nBULLET::::- 1528 – Archduchess Anna of Austria (d. 1590)\nBULLET::::- 1540 – John Sigismund Zápolya, King of Hungary (d. 1571)\nBULLET::::- 1586 – Thomas Howard, 21st Earl of Arundel, English courtier and politician, Lord Lieutenant of Northumberland (d. 1646)\nBULLET::::- 1616 – John Leverett, Governor of Massachusetts Bay Colony (d. 1679)\nBULLET::::- 1752 – Joseph Marie Jacquard, French merchant, invented the Jacquard loom (d. 1834)\nBULLET::::- 1766 – Guillaume Philibert Duhesme, French general (d. 1815)\nBULLET::::- 1831 – Jane Elizabeth Conklin, American poet and religious writer (d. 1914)\nBULLET::::- 1833 – Félicien Rops, Belgian painter and illustrator (d. 1898)\nBULLET::::- 1843 – Camillo Golgi, Italian physician and pathologist, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1926)\nBULLET::::- 1846 – Heinrich Rosenthal, Estonian physician and author (d. 1916)\nBULLET::::- 1848 – Francisco de Paula Rodrigues Alves, Brazilian politician, 5th President of Brazil (d. 1919)\nB