{"id": "15864", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15864", "title": "June 8", "text": "June 8\n\nBULLET::::- 218 – Battle of Antioch: With the support of the Syrian legions, Elagabalus defeats the forces of emperor Macrinus. He flees, but is captured near Chalcedon and later executed in Cappadocia.\nBULLET::::- 632 – Muhammad, Islamic prophet, dies in Medina.\nBULLET::::- 793 – Vikings raid the abbey at Lindisfarne in Northumbria, commonly accepted as the beginning of Norse activity in the British Isles.\nBULLET::::- 1042 – Edward the Confessor becomes King of England, one of the last Anglo-Saxon kings of England.\nBULLET::::- 1191 – Richard I arrives in Acre, beginning his crusade.\nBULLET::::- 1405 – Richard le Scrope, the Archbishop of York, and Thomas Mowbray, Earl of Norfolk, are executed in York on Henry IV's orders.\nBULLET::::- 1663 – Portuguese victory at the Battle of Ameixial ensures Protugal's independence from Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1776 – American Revolutionary War: American attackers are driven back at the Battle of Trois-Rivières.\nBULLET::::- 1783 – Laki, a volcano in Iceland, begins an eight-month eruption which kills over 9,000 people and starts a seven-year famine.\nBULLET::::- 1789 – James Madison introduces twelve proposed amendments to the United States Constitution in Congress.\nBULLET::::- 1794 – Robespierre inaugurates the French Revolution's new state religion, the Cult of the Supreme Being, with large organized festivals all across France.\nBULLET::::- 1856 – A group of 194 Pitcairn Islanders, descendants of the mutineers of , arrives at Norfolk Island, commencing the Third Settlement of the Island.\nBULLET::::- 1861 – American Civil War: Tennessee secedes from the Union.\nBULLET::::- 1862 – American Civil War: Battle of Cross Keys: Confederate forces under General Stonewall Jackson save the Army of Northern Virginia from a Union assault on the James Peninsula led by General George B. McClellan.\nBULLET::::- 1867 – Coronation of Franz Joseph as King of Hungary following the Austro-Hungarian compromise (\"Ausgleich\").\nBULLET::::- 1887 – Herman Hollerith applies for US patent #395,781 for the 'Art of Compiling Statistics', which was his punched card calculator.\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Theodore Roosevelt signs the Antiquities Act into law, authorizing the President to restrict the use of certain parcels of public land with historical or conservation value.\nBULLET::::- 1912 – Carl Laemmle incorporates Universal Pictures.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – A solar eclipse is observed at Baker City, Oregon by scientists and an artist hired by the United States Navy.\nBULLET::::- 1928 – Second Northern Expedition: The National Revolutionary Army captures Peking, whose name is changed to Beijing (\"Northern Capital\").\nBULLET::::- 1929 – Margaret Bondfield is appointed Minister of Labour. She is the first woman appointed to the Cabinet of the United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – World War II: The completion of Operation Alphabet, the evacuation of Allied forces from Narvik at the end of the Norwegian Campaign.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: The Allies commence the Syria–Lebanon Campaign against the possessions of Vichy France in the Levant.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: The Japanese imperial submarines I-21 and I-24 shell the Australian cities of Sydney and Newcastle.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – Helen Keller, Dorothy Parker, Danny Kaye, Fredric March, John Garfield, Paul Muni and Edward G. Robinson are named in an FBI report as Communist Party members.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – George Orwell's \"Nineteen Eighty-Four\" is published.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – An F5 tornado hits Beecher, Michigan, killing 116, injuring 844, and destroying 340 homes.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – The United States Supreme Court rules in \"District of Columbia v. John R. Thompson Co.\" that restaurants in Washington, D.C., cannot refuse to serve black patrons.\nBULLET::::- 1959 – and the United States Postal Service attempt the delivery of mail via Missile Mail.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – An F-104 Starfighter collides with XB-70 Valkyrie prototype no. 2, destroying both aircraft during a photo shoot near Edwards Air Force Base. Joseph A. Walker, a NASA test pilot, and Carl Cross, a United States Air Force test pilot, are both killed.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – Topeka, Kansas, is devastated by a tornado that registers as an \"F5\" on the Fujita scale: The first to exceed US$100 million in damages. Sixteen people are killed, hundreds more injured, and thousands of homes damaged or destroyed.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – The National Football League and American Football League announced a merger effective in 1970.\nBULLET::::- 1967 – Six-Day War: The USS \"Liberty\" incident occurs, killing 34 and wounding 171.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Vietnam War: Nine-year-old Phan Thị Kim Phúc is burned by napalm, an event captured by Associated Press photographer Nick Ut moments later while the young girl is seen running down a road, in what would become an iconic, Pulitzer Prize-winning photo.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – Bluff Cove Air Attacks during the Falklands War: Fifty-six British servicemen are killed by an Argentine air attack on two landing ships, and .\nBULLET::::- 1984 – Homosexuality is declared legal in the Australian state of New South Wales.\nBULLET::::- 1987 – New Zealand's Labour government establishes a national nuclear-free zone under the New Zealand Nuclear Free Zone, Disarmament, and Arms Control Act 1987.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – The first World Oceans Day is celebrated, coinciding with the Earth Summit held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – Downed U.S. Air Force pilot Captain Scott O'Grady is rescued by U.S. Marines in Bosnia.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – Mamoru Takuma kills eight and injures 15 in a mass stabbing at an elementary school in the Osaka Prefecture of Japan.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The first Venus Transit in well over a century takes place, the previous one being in 1882.\nBULLET::::- 2007 – Newcastle, New South Wales, Australia, is hit by the State's worst storms and flooding in 30 years resulting in the death of nine people and the grounding of a trade ship, the .\nBULLET::::- 2008 – At least 37 miners go missing after an explosion in a Ukrainian coal mine causes it to collapse.\nBULLET::::- 2008 – At least seven people are killed and ten injured in a stabbing spree in Tokyo, Japan.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – Two American journalists are found guilty of illegally entering North Korea and sentenced to 12 years of penal labour.\nBULLET::::- 2014 – At least 28 people are killed in an attack at Jinnah International Airport, Karachi, Pakistan.\n\nBULLET::::- 862 – Emperor Xizong of Tang (d. 888)\nBULLET::::- 1236 – Violant of Aragon, queen consort of Castile and León (d. 1301)\nBULLET::::- 1332 – Cangrande II della Scala, Lord of Verona (d. 1359)\nBULLET::::- 1508 – Primož Trubar, Slovenian Protestant reformer (d. 1586)\nBULLET::::- 1552 – Gabriello Chiabrera, Italian poet and author (d. 1638)\nBULLET::::- 1593 – George I Rákóczi, prince of Transylvania (d. 1648)\nBULLET::::- 1625 – Giovanni Domenico Cassini, Italian-French mathematician and astronomer (d. 1712)\nBULLET::::- 1671 – Tomaso Albinoni, Italian violinist and composer (d. 1751)\nBULLET::::- 1717 – John Collins, American lawyer and politician, 3rd Governor of Rhode Island (d. 1795)\nBULLET::::- 1724 – John Smeaton, English engineer, designed the Coldstream Bridge and Perth Bridge (d. 1794)\nBULLET::::- 1745 – Caspar Wessel, Norwegian-Danish mathematician and cartographer (d. 1818)\nBULLET::::- 1757 – Ercole Consalvi, Italian cardinal (d. 1824)\nBULLET::::- 1788 – Charles A. Wickliffe, American politician, 14th Governor of Kentucky (d. 1869)\nBULLET::::- 1810 – Robert Schumann, German composer and critic (d. 1856)\nBULLET::::- 1829 – John Everett Millais, English painter and illustrator (d. 1896)\nBULLET::::- 1831 – Thomas J. Higgins, Canadian-American sergeant, Medal of Honor recipient (d. 1917)\nBULLET::::- 1842 – John Q. A. Brackett, American lawyer